<p>The <code>detail</code> key should tell the API client <em>any</em> other information about what went
wrong. And check this out: when the <code>start()</code> method is called, it has an optional
<code>$authException</code> argument. Most of the time, when Symfony calls <code>start()</code> its because
an <code>AuthenticationException</code> has been thrown. And <em>this</em> class gives us some information
about <em>what</em> caused this situation.</p>
<p>And in fact, in <code>TokenController</code>, we're throwing a <code>BadCredentialsException</code>, which
is a sub-class of <code>AuthenticationException</code>. Hold <code>command</code> to look inside the class:</p>
